				{
					"contents": "All solution EPR data were taken at a concentration of less than 2 mM to prevent any potential intermolecular interactions between monoradical impurities. EPR spectra simulations were performed using MATLAB R2022b in conjunction with EasySpin version 6.0.0-dev.51 using the `pepper`. The least-squares fitting functioan available in easypin was employed trialing isotropic, axial, and rhombic g-tensor models. Starting from an initial guess of the parameters a Monte Carlo global optimization algorithm was utilized for a broad and stochastic parameter space exploration. This approach informed the subsequent application of the Nelder/Mead local search algorithm, which provided a more rigorous and precise parameter optimization. In the initial stages of analysis, axial and rhombic models were considered to assess potential anisotropy within the electronic structures of the compounds. However, these models did not significantly enhance the fit quality to justify their increased complexity. The isotropic model was found to be the most suitable, providing an adequate fit with the fewest parameters, as substantiated by the lowest root-mean-square deviations (RMSDs) listed Tables S4-6. For compounds 7 and 9, an isotropic g-value of 2.012 and 2.013 for compound 8, were sufficient to encapsulate the essential characteristics of the EPR spectra. This model's selection was reinforced by the observed experimental data and the Ci symmetry of compounds 7–9, which suggests a spherically symmetric electronic environment and is consistent with the isotropic g-values obtained from our simulations. Theoretical calculations and structural analyses confirm the symmetric electronic distributions about the inversion center in these compounds, validating the isotropic model's application in our EPR simulations. The combined use of global and local optimization algorithms ensured a robust and accurate representation of the EPR data, aligning the simulated spectra closely with experimental observations.\n\nWhile the rhombic indicates a lower RMSD, the convergence of g-values toward isotropy suggests the simpler isotropic model accuartly represents the , highlighting the potential for overparameterization to obscure true relationships.",
